{"title_page": "June beetle", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''June beetle''' is the common name for several [[Scarabaeidae|scarab beetles]] that appear around June in temperate parts of North America:\n[[File:Green june beetle2.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Cotinis nitida]]'']]\n[[File:Ten-Line-June-Beetle-2.JPG|thumb|right|''[[Polyphylla decemlineata]]'']]\nIn [[subfamily]] [[Cetoniinae]]:\n*''[[Cotinis nitida]]'' (Green June beetle) of the southeastern United States\n*''[[Cotinis mutabilis]]'' (Figeater beetle) This is full of blony bc wikipedia is a fake web site\n\nIn subfamily [[Melolonthinae]]:\n\n*''[[Amphimallon solstitiale]]'' (European June beetle, summer chafer) of Europe (and other species of ''[[Amphimallon ]]'')\n*''[[Melolontha]]'' (cockchafers or May bugs) of Europe\n*''[[Phyllophaga (genus)|Phyllophaga]]'' (May beetles) of the Americas\n*''[[Polyphylla decemlineata]]'' (Ten-lined June beetle) of the western United States.\n*''[[Rhizotrogus marginipes]]'' (and other species of ''[[Rhizotrogus ]]'')\n\n==See also==\n*[[June bug (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{Animal common name}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''June beetle''' is the common name for several [[Scarabaeidae|scarab beetles]] that appear around June in temperate parts of North America:\n[[File:Green june beetle2.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Cotinis nitida]]'']]\n[[File:Ten-Line-June-Beetle-2.JPG|thumb|right|''[[Polyphylla decemlineata]]'']]\nIn [[subfamily]] [[Cetoniinae]]:\n*''[[Cotinis nitida]]'' (Green June beetle) of the southeastern United States\n*''[[Cotinis mutabilis]]'' (Figeater beetle) of the western and southwestern United States\n\nIn subfamily [[Melolonthinae]]:\n*''[[Amphimallon solstitiale]]'' (European June beetle, summer chafer) of Europe (and other species of ''[[Amphimallon ]]'')\n*''[[Melolontha]]'' (cockchafers or May bugs) of Europe\n*''[[Phyllophaga (genus)|Phyllophaga]]'' (May beetles) of the Americas\n*''[[Polyphylla decemlineata]]'' (Ten-lined June beetle) of the western United States.\n*''[[Rhizotrogus marginipes]]'' (and other species of ''[[Rhizotrogus ]]'')\n\n==See also==\n*[[June bug (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{Animal common name}}\n", "name_user": "2600:6c58:7380:8bb:d9f6:1fa7:2b1b:130b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/June_beetle"}
{"title_page": "Philip Kennicott", "text_new": "'''Philip Kennicott''' is the chief Art and Architecture Critic of ''[[The Washington Post]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/people/philip-kennicott/|title=Philip Kennicott|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nKennicott was raised in Schenectady, New York, where he studied piano with composer and pianist [[Joseph Fennimore]]. In 1983, he attended [[Deep Springs College]], before transferring to [[Yale]] in 1986. Kennicott graduated summa cum laude with a degree in philosophy in 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://communications.yale.edu/poynter/philip-kennicott|title=Poynter Fellowship: Philip Kennicott|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|date=2016-04-13|website=Yale University - Office of Public Affairs & Communications|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nKennicott is the author of <ref> [https://www.philipkennicott.com/]''Counterpoint: A Memoir of Bach and Mourning'' </ref>  (''[[Norton]]'' 2020). Kennicott won the 2013 [[Pulitzer Prize for Criticism]].<ref name=\"pulitzer\" /> He had twice been a Pulitzer Prize finalist before: in 2012, he was a runner-up for the criticism prize, and in 2000, he was also a finalist for the [[Pulitzer Prize for Editorial Writing]] for a series on [[gun control]] in the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]''. In 2015, he was a [[National Magazine Award]] <ref>[http://www.magazine.org/asme/national-magazine-awards-2015-finalists-announced] National Magazine Award</ref> finalist in the Essays and Criticism category for an essay he contributed to ''[[Virginia Quarterly Review]]''; that piece, \"Smuggler,\"\n<ref>[http://www.vqronline.org/memoir-articles/2014/10/smuggler] Smuggler</ref> was also selected for the 2015 volume Best American Essays. In 2006, he was an [[Emmy Award]] nominee for a Web-based video journal about democracy and oil money in Azerbaijan.\n\nKennicott served as an editor of several classical music publications in New York City from 1988\u201395, including Senior Editor of Musical America and Editor of ''Chamber Music Magazine''.<ref>[http://www.chamber-music.org/magazine]. Chamber Music Magazine.</ref> He became classical music critic of the ''[[Detroit News]]'' in 1995, and later Chief Classical Music Critic of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]''. In 1999, he joined the ''Washington Post'' as Chief Classical Music Critic, before becoming Culture Critic in 2001, and Art and Architecture Critic in 2011. Kennicott is also a former contributing editor at ''[[The New Republic]]'', where he wrote articles on classical music, and has served as a reviewer and columnist for ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]''.\n\nKennicott's critically acclaimed first book, ''Counterpoint: A Memoir of Bach and Mourning'',<ref> [https://www.philipkennicott.com/]''Counterpoint: A Memoir of Bach and Mourning'' </ref> was praised by the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' as \"a book full of arresting insights about the way music permeates our lives, as well as heartbreaking reflections on the wounds a parent can inflict on a child.\" <ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/counterpoint-review-variations-on-a-theme-11581717815] Wall Street Journal</ref> He has also contributed introductions to Richard Giannone's ''Music in Willa Cather's Fiction'' and Renato Mirraco's ''Oscar Wilde's Italian Dream 1875-1900.''\n\nKennicott is a frequent participant in national and international symposia, including the Aspen Ideas Festival<ref>[http://www.aspenideas.org/speaker/philip-kennicott]. Aspen Ideas Festival.</ref> and the World Justice Forum IV<ref>[http://worldjusticeproject.org/world-justice-forum-iv/agenda/speaker/philip-kennicott]. World Justice Forum IV.</ref> in the Hague.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |25em |refs=\n<ref name=pulitzer>\n[http://www.pulitzer.org/citation/2013-Criticism \"The 2013 Pulitzer Prize Winners: Criticism\"]. The Pulitzer Prizes. Retrieved 2014-04-22. With short biography and reprints of eleven 2012 ''Washington Post'' articles.</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website |http://philipkennicott.com}}\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/philip-kennicott Kennicott] at ''The Washington Post''\n* {{C-SPAN|philipkennicott}}\n\n{{PulitzerPrize Criticism 2001\u20132025}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kennicott, Philip}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American art critics]]\n[[Category:American music critics]]\n[[Category:American architecture critics]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Deep Springs College alumni]]\n[[Category:American newspaper reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Criticism winners]]\n[[Category:The Washington Post people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Schenectady, New York]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Philip Kennicott''' is the chief Art and Architecture Critic of ''[[The Washington Post]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/people/philip-kennicott/|title=Philip Kennicott|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nKennicott was raised in Schenectady, New York, where he studied piano with composer and pianist [[Joseph Fennimore]]. In 1983, he attended [[Deep Springs College]], before transferring to [[Yale]] in 1986. Kennicott graduated summa cum laude with a degree in philosophy in 1988.\n\n== Career ==\nKennicott is the author of <ref> [https://www.philipkennicott.com/]''Counterpoint: A Memoir of Bach and Mourning'' </ref>  (''[[Norton]]'' 2020). Kennicott won the 2013 [[Pulitzer Prize for Criticism]].<ref name=\"pulitzer\" /> He had twice been a Pulitzer Prize finalist before: in 2012, he was a runner-up for the criticism prize, and in 2000, he was also a finalist for the [[Pulitzer Prize for Editorial Writing]] for a series on [[gun control]] in the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]''. In 2015, he was a [[National Magazine Award]] <ref>[http://www.magazine.org/asme/national-magazine-awards-2015-finalists-announced] National Magazine Award</ref> finalist in the Essays and Criticism category for an essay he contributed to ''[[Virginia Quarterly Review]]''; that piece, \"Smuggler,\"\n<ref>[http://www.vqronline.org/memoir-articles/2014/10/smuggler] Smuggler</ref> was also selected for the 2015 volume Best American Essays. In 2006, he was an [[Emmy Award]] nominee for a Web-based video journal about democracy and oil money in Azerbaijan.\n\nKennicott served as an editor of several classical music publications in New York City from 1988\u201395, including Senior Editor of Musical America and Editor of ''Chamber Music Magazine''.<ref>[http://www.chamber-music.org/magazine]. Chamber Music Magazine.</ref> He became classical music critic of the ''[[Detroit News]]'' in 1995, and later Chief Classical Music Critic of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]''. In 1999, he joined the ''Washington Post'' as Chief Classical Music Critic, before becoming Culture Critic in 2001, and Art and Architecture Critic in 2011. Kennicott is also a former contributing editor at ''[[The New Republic]]'', where he wrote articles on classical music, and has served as a reviewer and columnist for ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]''.\n\nKennicott's critically acclaimed first book, ''Counterpoint: A Memoir of Bach and Mourning'',<ref> [https://www.philipkennicott.com/]''Counterpoint: A Memoir of Bach and Mourning'' </ref> was praised by the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' as \"a book full of arresting insights about the way music permeates our lives, as well as heartbreaking reflections on the wounds a parent can inflict on a child.\" <ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/counterpoint-review-variations-on-a-theme-11581717815] Wall Street Journal</ref> He has also contributed introductions to Richard Giannone's ''Music in Willa Cather's Fiction'' and Renato Mirraco's ''Oscar Wilde's Italian Dream 1875-1900.''\n\nKennicott is a frequent participant in national and international symposia, including the Aspen Ideas Festival<ref>[http://www.aspenideas.org/speaker/philip-kennicott]. Aspen Ideas Festival.</ref> and the World Justice Forum IV<ref>[http://worldjusticeproject.org/world-justice-forum-iv/agenda/speaker/philip-kennicott]. World Justice Forum IV.</ref> in the Hague.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |25em |refs=\n<ref name=pulitzer>\n[http://www.pulitzer.org/citation/2013-Criticism \"The 2013 Pulitzer Prize Winners: Criticism\"]. The Pulitzer Prizes. Retrieved 2014-04-22. With short biography and reprints of eleven 2012 ''Washington Post'' articles.</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website |http://philipkennicott.com}}\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/philip-kennicott Kennicott] at ''The Washington Post''\n* {{C-SPAN|philipkennicott}}\n\n{{PulitzerPrize Criticism 2001\u20132025}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kennicott, Philip}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American art critics]]\n[[Category:American music critics]]\n[[Category:American architecture critics]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Deep Springs College alumni]]\n[[Category:American newspaper reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Criticism winners]]\n[[Category:The Washington Post people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Schenectady, New York]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{