{"title_page": "Lauren Grodstein", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer  \n| name          = Lauren Grodstein \n| image         = Lauren Grodstein 5190132.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1975|11|19}}\n| birth_place   = New York City\n| occupation    = Writer, Educator \n| language      = English\n| nationality   = American \n| education     = Columbia University, B.A., 1997, M.F.A, 2001\n| spouse        = Ben Freeman (musician) \n| children      = Nathaniel, Penelope  \n| awards        = Philolexian Prize, Columbia University, 1997; New York Public Library \u201cBook for the Teen Age\u201d list, 2006, for ''Girls Dinner Club''\n}}\n\n'''Lauren Grodstein''' (born November 19, 1975) is an American novelist and professor at [[Rutgers University-Camden]] who is known for her use of male characters and family narratives.  Her novels, the New York Times-bestselling \"A Friend of the Family,\" along with \"The Explanation for Everything\" were Washington Post Books of the Year, and \"A Friend of the Family\" was a New York Times Editors' Choice.  ''Girls Dinner Club'' made the [[New York Public Library]] \u201cBook for the Teen Age\u201d list in 2006.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n==Background==\nLauren Grodstein grew up in North Jersey, in a Jewish family,<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\">{{cite encyclopedia|title= Lauren Grodstein|encyclopedia=Contemporary Authors Online|publisher=Gale|year=2011}}</ref><ref name= \"Take Me Out to the Election\">{{cite news|last=Grodstein|first=Lauren|title=Take Me Out to the Election|newspaper= New York Times|date= November 1, 2009}}</ref> and has family members in France who survived the Holocaust.<ref name=myjewishlearning>{{cite web |url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/blog/members-of-the-scribe/author/lgrodstein/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029213743/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/blog/members-of-the-scribe/author/lgrodstein/ |archivedate=October 29, 2013  }}</ref>  When she was younger she had an active imagination, and loved to trick her friends and family into believing her made up stories. Grodstein now lives in Moorestown, New Jersey with her husband, Ben, and son, Nathaniel, and considers herself to be a \"reluctant atheist.\"<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\" /><ref name=\"Radiotimes\">{{cite interview|title= A Conversation with Local Novelist Lauren Grodstein|url= http://whyy.org/cms/radiotimes/2013/09/30/a-conversation-with-local-novelist-lauren-grodstein/| publisher= WHYY| work= Radiotimes|date= September 30, 2013|minutes=52.01}}</ref> She teaches creative writing at Rutgers Camden to a wide variety of students.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\" /><ref name= \"Take Me Out to the Election\" /> When she is not teaching, she is writing fiction, including several award-winning novels, and an unpublished book.<ref name=\"FamilyAffairs\">{{cite journal|last= Teicher|first= Craig|title= Family Affairs|newspaper= Publishers Weekly|date= September 21, 2009| page=25}}</ref> The novels that she has published are known for depicting the faults of suburbia, especially ''A Friend of the Family''.<ref name=Suburbia>{{cite news|title=Trouble in Suburbia| newspaper= The Jerusalem Post| date= January 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nGrodstein attended high school in northeastern New Jersey.<ref name=\"WORDInterview\">{{cite interview |subject= Lauren Grodstein |interviewer= WORD Brooklyn Blog |title= In Conversation With Lauren Grodstein |url= http://wordbrooklyn.wordpress.com/2010/11/02/in-conversation-with-lauren-grodstein/ |location= Brooklyn|date=November 2, 2010 |accessdate= October 10, 2013}}</ref> After graduating, she attended Columbia University, receiving her Bachelor of Arts in English in 1997 and a Master of Fine Arts in Creative Writing in 2001.<ref>\"Lauren Grodstein.\" Contemporary Authors Online. Detroit: Gale, 2011. Literature Resource Center. Web. Retrieved October 8, 2013. url=[http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CH1000152523&v=2.1&u=richstockcol&it=r&p=LitRC&sw=w&asid=989108187ff7b9eb378e51ebf4351f3a]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn addition to being an author, Grodstein is also a college English professor,<ref>{{cite web|title=About the Author Lauren Grodstein: Author of The Explanation for Everything and A Friend of the Family|url=http://laurengrodstein.com/about-the-author/.|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ContempAuthors\">{{cite web|title=Contemporary Authors Online. Detroit: Gale, 2011. Literature Resource Center|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CH1000152523&v=2.1&it=r&p=LitRC&sw=w&asid=989108187ff7b9eb378e51ebf4351f3a|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>  beginning her teaching career at [[Columbia University|Columbia University in New York]] from 1999 to 2001, and acting as an adjunct professor in the creative writing department in 2004. Grodstein taught creative writing at [[UCLA|The University of California in Los Angeles]] and [[Cooper Union|Cooper Union in New York]] from 2003 to 2004. In 2005, Grodstein became an assistant professor of English at Rutgers University-Camden, where she currently works as an associate English professor and teaches creative writing, modern drama, and fiction and nonfiction courses.<ref name=\"ContempAuthors\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty {{!}} Department of English, Rutgers University|url=http://english.camden.rutgers.edu/faculty/|accessdate=October 24, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192728/http://english.camden.rutgers.edu/faculty/|archivedate=October 29, 2013}}</ref>  She is also a member of the Department of Childhood Studies.<ref name=\"ChildhoodDeptRUC\">{{cite web|title=Faculty {{!}} Department of Childhood Studies, Rutgers University.|url=http://childhood.camden.rutgers.edu/faculty/|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nGrodstein has published six books to date.  Five of her novels were written under her real name while one, ''Girls Dinner Club'', was released under the pseudonym of Jesse Elliot.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''The Best of Animals'' (2002)===\nGrodstein's debut is a short story collection including ten stories, many of which share a theme of characters keeping their personal feelings to themselves and rarely saying what they mean.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/> Critics generally responded well to ''The Best of Animals,'' calling it \"lively\" and praising Grodstein's \"quirky voice and sassy, ironic humor\" which \"make these stories come alive\".<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''Reproduction is the Flaw of Love'' (2004)===\n''Reproduction is the Flaw of Love'' is Grodstein's first novel, and also her first story told from the point of view of a male character. The protagonist is a man named Joe who reflects on his life, his relationships, and his parents' failed marriage while waiting to learn the results of his girlfriend's pregnancy test, mainly considering the type of bond he would want to have with his own kids in comparison to the one he had with his parents.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/> This novel was described as an \"insightful study of our search for meaningful connections\u201d by critic Beth Leistensnider.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''Girls Dinner Club'' (2005)===\n''Girls Dinner Club'', written under a pseudonym, is about three 17-year-old best friends who meet weekly to eat, gossip about their lives, and to lean on each other for emotional support.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''[[A Friend of the Family]]'' (2009)===\n''[[A Friend of the Family]]'', according to Grodstein, is \u201cabout family and loving your kids. And both dads in the book do.\u201d <ref>''A Friend of the Family''. (2009). ''Publishers Weekly'', 256(51), 56.</ref> The novel details the tragic consequences that result when the main character, a doctor named Pete Dizinoff, tries to prevent his college-aged son from becoming romantically involved with his best friend's much older, troubled daughter.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''An Explanation for Everything'' (2013)===\nA novel about the loss of love and belief, telling the story of a college professor named Andy, who's still coping with the death of his wife when he agrees to take on an independent study course for a female student with spiritual views very different from his own.<ref>\"Grodstein, Lauren: THE EXPLANATION FOR EVERYTHING.\" Kirkus Reviews September 15, 2013.Literature Resource Center. Web. October 9, 2013.</ref>\n\n===''Our Short History'' (2017)===\nGrodstein's most recent book is about a single mother, Karen, who is writing a memoir for her son, Jake, to read after she passes away.  The novel was called \"one of the best of 2017\" by several critics.\n\n==Influences==\n\nGrodstein states that literature has been a natural interest for her since she was a child. Though always surrounded by artistic influences, she attributes the development of her literary skills to her grandmother.<ref name=\"Lauren's First Interview\">{{cite web|last=Vogt-Hennessy|first=Chris|title=Interview with Lauren Grodstein|work=Literarymama|url=http://www.literarymama.com/profiles/archives/2010/09/an-interview-with-lauren-grods.html}}</ref> Grodstein often sets her stories in New Jersey, where she grew up and now teaches college, claiming that her home state has always been close to her life and art. With the release of her novel ''Reproduction is the Flaw of Love'', Grodstein expanded her skills as a writer to the creation of male characters, stating that her choice of mostly male protagonists serves as a way to avoid \"Mary Sue\"-ism.<ref name=\"BookBrowseInterview\">{{cite interview |last=Grodstein |first=Lauren|interviewer=Tom Perrotta |title=An Interview With Lauren Grodstein |url=http://www.bookbrowse.com/author_interviews/full/index.cfm/author_number/2282/lauren-grodstein |accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGrodstein was born on November 19, 1975, in New York City. She was raised in a Jewish family by her mother Adele, a painter, and her father Gerald, a physician.<ref>\"Lauren Grodstein\" - Literature Resource Center</ref> She has a younger sister and a younger brother.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/10/style/weddings-celebrations-jessica-grodstein-iain-kennedy.html|title=WEDDINGS/CELEBRATIONS; Jessica Grodstein, Iain Kennedy|date=August 10, 2003|accessdate=May 20, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> She currently lives in Moorestown, New Jersey with her husband Ben, a musician, their son Nate and daughter Penny, and her Bernese Mountain Dog.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/news/local/burlington_county_times_news/lauren-grodstein/image_42e8e19f-1871-5469-98e8-933b83377f06.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131024142512/http://www.phillyburbs.com/news/local/burlington_county_times_news/lauren-grodstein/image_42e8e19f-1871-5469-98e8-933b83377f06.html |archivedate=October 24, 2013  }}</ref> She wrote a ''New York Times'' article on October 31, 2009, entitled \"Take Me to the Election\" <ref name=\"TakeMeToTheElection\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/01/opinion/01grodstein.html|title=Opinion - Take Me Out to the Election|first=Lauren|last=Grodstein|date=October 31, 2009|accessdate=May 20, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> in which she talks about New Jersey's upcoming gubernatorial election and the challenges of discussing it with her class.<ref name=\"TakeMeToTheElection\"/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nIn 1997, Grodstein was nominated for the [[Philolexian Society|Philolexian Prize]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wikicu.com/Philolexian_Prize |title=Philolexian Prize |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 12, 2013 |website=WikiCU |publisher=Columbia University |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref> a [[Columbia University]] award for literary work. Her novel ''A Friend of the Family'' has been selected as a ''New York Times'' Bestseller, ''Washington Post'' Book of the Year, an [[Amazon.com Best Books|Amazon.com Best Book]], and a ''January Magazine'' Top Ten Book of the Year,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.camden.rutgers.edu/2013/08/rutgers-camden-to-host-writers-in-camden-series-first-readings-set-for-sept-11/ |title=First Readings Set For September 11 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Rutgers Camden News Now |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref> as well as a ''New York Times'' Editor's Pick.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.booksmith.com/event/lauren-grostein-talks-eith-adam-mansbach-explanation-everything |title=LAUREN GRODSTEIN talks with ADAM MANSBACH / The Explanation for Everything |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 8, 2013 |website=Booksmith |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref> ''Girls Dinner Club'' was nominated as a New York Public Library Book for the Teen Age.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.booktowne.com/event/lauren-grodstein-explanation-everything |title=About the Author |last1=Hwalsh |date= July 8, 2013|website=Booktowne |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grodstein, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:Cooper Union faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Columbia University School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer  \n| name          = Lauren Grodstein \n| image         = Lauren Grodstein 5190132.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1975|11|19}}\n| birth_place   = New York City\n| occupation    = Writer, Educator \n| language      = English\n| nationality   = American \n| education     = Columbia University, B.A., 1997, M.F.A, 2001\n| spouse        = Ben Freeman (musician) \n| children      = Nathaniel, Penelope  \n| awards        = Philolexian Prize, Columbia University, 1997; New York Public Library \u201cBook for the Teen Age\u201d list, 2006, for ''Girls Dinner Club''\n}}\n\n'''Lauren Grodstein''' (born November 19, 1975) is an American novelist and professor at [[Rutgers University-Camden]] who is known for her use of male characters and family narratives.  Her novels, the New York Times-bestselling \"A Friend of the Family,\" along with \"The Explanation for Everything\" were Washington Post Books of the Year, and \"A Friend of the Family\" was a New York Times Editors' Choice.  ''Girls Dinner Club'' made the [[New York Public Library]] \u201cBook for the Teen Age\u201d list in 2006.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n==Background==\nLauren Grodstein grew up in North Jersey, in a Jewish family,<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\">{{cite encyclopedia|title= Lauren Grodstein|encyclopedia=Contemporary Authors Online|publisher=Gale|year=2011}}</ref><ref name= \"Take Me Out to the Election\">{{cite news|last=Grodstein|first=Lauren|title=Take Me Out to the Election|newspaper= New York Times|date= November 1, 2009}}</ref> and has family members in France who survived the Holocaust.<ref name=myjewishlearning>{{cite web |url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/blog/members-of-the-scribe/author/lgrodstein/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029213743/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/blog/members-of-the-scribe/author/lgrodstein/ |archivedate=October 29, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  When she was younger she had an active imagination, and loved to trick her friends and family into believing her made up stories. Grodstein now lives in Moorestown, New Jersey with her husband, Ben, and son, Nathaniel, and considers herself to be a \"reluctant atheist.\"<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\" /><ref name=\"Radiotimes\">{{cite interview|title= A Conversation with Local Novelist Lauren Grodstein|url= http://whyy.org/cms/radiotimes/2013/09/30/a-conversation-with-local-novelist-lauren-grodstein/| publisher= WHYY| work= Radiotimes|date= September 30, 2013|minutes=52.01}}</ref> She teaches creative writing at Rutgers Camden to a wide variety of students.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\" /><ref name= \"Take Me Out to the Election\" /> When she is not teaching, she is writing fiction, including several award-winning novels, and an unpublished book.<ref name=\"FamilyAffairs\">{{cite journal|last= Teicher|first= Craig|title= Family Affairs|newspaper= Publishers Weekly|date= September 21, 2009| page=25}}</ref> The novels that she has published are known for depicting the faults of suburbia, especially ''A Friend of the Family''.<ref name=Suburbia>{{cite news|title=Trouble in Suburbia| newspaper= The Jerusalem Post| date= January 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nGrodstein attended high school in northeastern New Jersey.<ref name=\"WORDInterview\">{{cite interview |subject= Lauren Grodstein |interviewer= WORD Brooklyn Blog |title= In Conversation With Lauren Grodstein |url= http://wordbrooklyn.wordpress.com/2010/11/02/in-conversation-with-lauren-grodstein/ |location= Brooklyn|date=November 2, 2010 |accessdate= October 10, 2013}}</ref> After graduating, she attended Columbia University, receiving her Bachelor of Arts in English in 1997 and a Master of Fine Arts in Creative Writing in 2001.<ref>\"Lauren Grodstein.\" Contemporary Authors Online. Detroit: Gale, 2011. Literature Resource Center. Web. Retrieved October 8, 2013. url=[http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CH1000152523&v=2.1&u=richstockcol&it=r&p=LitRC&sw=w&asid=989108187ff7b9eb378e51ebf4351f3a]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn addition to being an author, Grodstein is also a college English professor,<ref>{{cite web|title=About the Author Lauren Grodstein: Author of The Explanation for Everything and A Friend of the Family|url=http://laurengrodstein.com/about-the-author/.|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ContempAuthors\">{{cite web|title=Contemporary Authors Online. Detroit: Gale, 2011. Literature Resource Center|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CH1000152523&v=2.1&it=r&p=LitRC&sw=w&asid=989108187ff7b9eb378e51ebf4351f3a|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>  beginning her teaching career at [[Columbia University|Columbia University in New York]] from 1999 to 2001, and acting as an adjunct professor in the creative writing department in 2004. Grodstein taught creative writing at [[UCLA|The University of California in Los Angeles]] and [[Cooper Union|Cooper Union in New York]] from 2003 to 2004. In 2005, Grodstein became an assistant professor of English at Rutgers University-Camden, where she currently works as an associate English professor and teaches creative writing, modern drama, and fiction and nonfiction courses.<ref name=\"ContempAuthors\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty {{!}} Department of English, Rutgers University|url=http://english.camden.rutgers.edu/faculty/|accessdate=October 24, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192728/http://english.camden.rutgers.edu/faculty/|archivedate=October 29, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  She is also a member of the Department of Childhood Studies.<ref name=\"ChildhoodDeptRUC\">{{cite web|title=Faculty {{!}} Department of Childhood Studies, Rutgers University.|url=http://childhood.camden.rutgers.edu/faculty/|accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nGrodstein has published six books to date.  Five of her novels were written under her real name while one, ''Girls Dinner Club'', was released under the pseudonym of Jesse Elliot.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''The Best of Animals'' (2002)===\nGrodstein's debut is a short story collection including ten stories, many of which share a theme of characters keeping their personal feelings to themselves and rarely saying what they mean.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/> Critics generally responded well to ''The Best of Animals,'' calling it \"lively\" and praising Grodstein's \"quirky voice and sassy, ironic humor\" which \"make these stories come alive\".<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''Reproduction is the Flaw of Love'' (2004)===\n''Reproduction is the Flaw of Love'' is Grodstein's first novel, and also her first story told from the point of view of a male character. The protagonist is a man named Joe who reflects on his life, his relationships, and his parents' failed marriage while waiting to learn the results of his girlfriend's pregnancy test, mainly considering the type of bond he would want to have with his own kids in comparison to the one he had with his parents.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/> This novel was described as an \"insightful study of our search for meaningful connections\u201d by critic Beth Leistensnider.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''Girls Dinner Club'' (2005)===\n''Girls Dinner Club'', written under a pseudonym, is about three 17-year-old best friends who meet weekly to eat, gossip about their lives, and to lean on each other for emotional support.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''[[A Friend of the Family]]'' (2009)===\n''[[A Friend of the Family]]'', according to Grodstein, is \u201cabout family and loving your kids. And both dads in the book do.\u201d <ref>''A Friend of the Family''. (2009). ''Publishers Weekly'', 256(51), 56.</ref> The novel details the tragic consequences that result when the main character, a doctor named Pete Dizinoff, tries to prevent his college-aged son from becoming romantically involved with his best friend's much older, troubled daughter.<ref name=\"Contemporary Authors Online\"/>\n\n===''An Explanation for Everything'' (2013)===\nA novel about the loss of love and belief, telling the story of a college professor named Andy, who's still coping with the death of his wife when he agrees to take on an independent study course for a female student with spiritual views very different from his own.<ref>\"Grodstein, Lauren: THE EXPLANATION FOR EVERYTHING.\" Kirkus Reviews September 15, 2013.Literature Resource Center. Web. Oct 9, 2013.</ref>\n\n===''Our Short History'' (2017)===\nGrodstein's most recent book is about a single mother, Karen, who is writing a memoir for her son, Jake, to read after she passes away.  The novel was called \"one of the best of 2017\" by several critics.\n\n==Influences==\n\nGrodstein states that literature has been a natural interest for her since she was a child. Though always surrounded by artistic influences, she attributes the development of her literary skills to her grandmother.<ref name=\"Lauren's First Interview\">{{cite web|last=Vogt-Hennessy|first=Chris|title=Interview with Lauren Grodstein|work=Literarymama|url=http://www.literarymama.com/profiles/archives/2010/09/an-interview-with-lauren-grods.html}}</ref> Grodstein often sets her stories in New Jersey, where she grew up and now teaches college, claiming that her home state has always been close to her life and art. With the release of her novel ''Reproduction is the Flaw of Love'', Grodstein expanded her skills as a writer to the creation of male characters, stating that her choice of mostly male protagonists serves as a way to avoid \"Mary Sue\"-ism.<ref name=\"BookBrowseInterview\">{{cite interview |last=Grodstein |first=Lauren|interviewer=Tom Perrotta |title=An Interview With Lauren Grodstein |url=http://www.bookbrowse.com/author_interviews/full/index.cfm/author_number/2282/lauren-grodstein |accessdate=22 Oct 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGrodstein was born on November 19, 1975, in New York City. She was raised in a Jewish family by her mother Adele, a painter, and her father Gerald, a physician.<ref>\"Lauren Grodstein\" - Literature Resource Center</ref> She has a younger sister and a younger brother.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/10/style/weddings-celebrations-jessica-grodstein-iain-kennedy.html|title=WEDDINGS/CELEBRATIONS; Jessica Grodstein, Iain Kennedy|date=August 10, 2003|accessdate=May 20, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> She currently lives in Moorestown, New Jersey with her husband Ben, a musician, their son Nate and daughter Penny, and her Bernese Mountain Dog.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/news/local/burlington_county_times_news/lauren-grodstein/image_42e8e19f-1871-5469-98e8-933b83377f06.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131024142512/http://www.phillyburbs.com/news/local/burlington_county_times_news/lauren-grodstein/image_42e8e19f-1871-5469-98e8-933b83377f06.html |archivedate=October 24, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She wrote a ''New York Times'' article on October 31, 2009, entitled \"Take Me to the Election\" <ref name=\"TakeMeToTheElection\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/01/opinion/01grodstein.html|title=Opinion - Take Me Out to the Election|first=Lauren|last=Grodstein|date=October 31, 2009|accessdate=May 20, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> in which she talks about New Jersey's upcoming gubernatorial election and the challenges of discussing it with her class.<ref name=\"TakeMeToTheElection\"/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nIn 1997, Grodstein was nominated for the [[Philolexian Society|Philolexian Prize]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wikicu.com/Philolexian_Prize |title=Philolexian Prize |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 12, 2013 |website=WikiCU |publisher=Columbia University |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref> a [[Columbia University]] award for literary work. Her novel ''A Friend of the Family'' has been selected as a ''New York Times'' Bestseller, ''Washington Post'' Book of the Year, an [[Amazon.com Best Books|Amazon.com Best Book]], and a ''January Magazine'' Top Ten Book of the Year,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.camden.rutgers.edu/2013/08/rutgers-camden-to-host-writers-in-camden-series-first-readings-set-for-sept-11/ |title=First Readings Set For September 11 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Rutgers Camden News Now |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref> as well as a ''New York Times'' Editor's Pick.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.booksmith.com/event/lauren-grostein-talks-eith-adam-mansbach-explanation-everything |title=LAUREN GRODSTEIN talks with ADAM MANSBACH / The Explanation for Everything |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 8, 2013 |website=Booksmith |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref> ''Girls Dinner Club'' was nominated as a New York Public Library Book for the Teen Age.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.booktowne.com/event/lauren-grodstein-explanation-everything |title=About the Author |last1=Hwalsh |date= July 8, 2013|website=Booktowne |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grodstein, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:Cooper Union faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Columbia University School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauren_Grodstein"}
{"title_page": "Freddy (Angolan footballer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Angolan footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Freddy\n| image =\n| fullname = Frederico Castro Roque Santos\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|8|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Malanje]], Angola       \n| height = {{convert|1.75|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1992\u20131998 | youthclubs1 = [[G.D. Estoril Praia|Estoril]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20132001 | clubs1 = [[G.D. Estoril Praia|Estoril]] | caps1 = 79 | goals1 = 21 \n| years2 = 2001\u20132005 | clubs2 = [[U.D. Leiria|Uni\u00e3o Leiria]] | caps2 = 89 | goals2 = 6\n| years3 = 2005 | clubs3 = [[Moreirense F.C.|Moreirense]] | caps3 = 10 | goals3 = 1 \n| years4 = 2006 | clubs4 = [[Al-Gharafa Sports Club|Al-Gharafa]] | caps4 = ? | goals4 = 4\n| years5 = 2006 | clubs5 = [[C.D. Aves|Aves]] | caps5 = 9 | goals5 = 0 \n| years6 = 2007 | clubs6 = [[Negeri Sembilan FA|Negeri Sembilan]] | caps6 = | goals6 =\n| years7 = 2007 | clubs7 = [[Doxa Katokopias FC|Doxa]] | caps7 = 7 | goals7 = 3\n| years8 = 2008 | clubs8 = [[Enosis Neon Paralimni FC|Enosis Neon]] | caps8 = 26 | goals8 = 13 \n| years9 = 2009\u20132011 | clubs9 = [[AEL Limassol]] | caps9 = 68 | goals9 = 24\n| years10 = 2011\u20132013 | clubs10 = [[AC Omonia|Omonia]] | caps10 = 53 | goals10 = 23\n| years11 = 2013 | clubs11 = [[C.D. Primeiro de Agosto|1\u00ba Agosto]] | caps11 = | goals11 =\n| years12 = 2014 | clubs12 = [[C.R. Ca\u00e1la|Ca\u00e1la]] | caps12 = 6 | goals12 = 1\n| totalcaps = 347 | totalgoals = 96\n| nationalyears1 = 2004\u20132005 | nationalteam1 = [[Angola national football team|Angola]] | nationalcaps1 = 11 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| club-update =\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n\n'''Frederico Castro Roque dos Santos''' (born 14 August 1979), known as '''Freddy''', is an [[Angola]]n retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\nHe spent most of his professional career in Portugal and [[Cyprus]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Malanje]], Freddy spent nine seasons at [[G.D. Estoril Praia]] \u2013 youth years comprised \u2013 playing two seasons in the [[Portuguese Second Division|Portuguese third division]] and one in [[Segunda Liga|the second]] as a senior. In [[2001\u201302 Primeira Liga|2001\u201302]] he made his [[Primeira Liga]] debut, being coached by a young [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]] and playing 22 matches (17 as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]]) as the team [[2002 UEFA Intertoto Cup|qualified]] to the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]; during four years, he only started in 16 of the league appearances he made.\n\nFreddy started 2005\u201306 with [[Moreirense F.C.]] in the second level, but transferred to [[Al-Gharafa Sports Club]] from [[Qatar]] in the next [[transfer window]]. He would also split the following campaign, between [[C.D. Aves]] (Portuguese top flight) and [[Malaysia]]'s [[Negeri Sembilan FA]], appearing in six [[AFC Cup]] games during his short spell with the latter and scoring three goals.<ref>[http://www.the-afc.com/en/afc-cup-2007/afc-cup-2007-schedule-results AFC Cup 2007 schedule and results]</ref>\n\nIn summer 2007, Freddy moved countries again, signing with [[Doxa Katokopias FC]] in Cyprus. In January of the following year, he stayed in the country and joined [[Enosis Neon Paralimni FC]].\n\nStill in Cyprus, in January 2009 Freddy signed for [[AEL Limassol]], scoring a combined 20 [[Cypriot First Division]] goals in his first two full seasons but seeing his team come out empty in silverware.\n\n==International career==\nFreddy appeared for [[Angola national football team|Angola]] during the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualification campaign]], scoring his only international goal in a 1\u20130 home win against [[Rwanda national football team|Rwanda]], on 5 September 2004.<ref>{{FIFA player|214349}}</ref> The ''Palancas Negras'' eventually qualified for the final stages in Germany \u2013 a first-ever \u2013 but he was overlooked for the final squad of 23.\n\n==Honours==\n'''Omonia'''\n*[[Cypriot Cup]]: [[2011\u201312 Cypriot Cup|2011\u201312]]\n*[[Cypriot Super Cup]]: 2012\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{NFT player|192}}\n*{{Soccerway|frederico-de-castro-roque-dos-santos/61449}}\n\n{{Cypriot First Division top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freddy}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Malanje Province]]\n[[Category:Portuguese people of Angolan descent]]\n[[Category:Angolan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Second Division players]]\n[[Category:G.D. Estoril Praia players]]\n[[Category:U.D. Leiria players]]\n[[Category:Moreirense F.C. players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Aves players]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League players]]\n[[Category:Al-Gharafa SC players]]\n[[Category:Malaysia Super League players]]\n[[Category:Negeri Sembilan FA players]]\n[[Category:Cypriot First Division players]]\n[[Category:Doxa Katokopias FC players]]\n[[Category:Enosis Neon Paralimni FC players]]\n[[Category:AEL Limassol players]]\n[[Category:AC Omonia players]]\n[[Category:Girabola players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Primeiro de Agosto players]]\n[[Category:C.R. Ca\u00e1la players]]\n[[Category:Angola international footballers]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate sportspeople in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate sportspeople in Cyprus]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Freddy\n| image =\n| fullname = Frederico Castro Roque Santos\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|8|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Malanje]], Angola       \n| height = {{convert|1.75|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1992\u20131998 | youthclubs1 = [[G.D. Estoril Praia|Estoril]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20132001 | clubs1 = [[G.D. Estoril Praia|Estoril]] | caps1 = 79 | goals1 = 21 \n| years2 = 2001\u20132005 | clubs2 = [[U.D. Leiria|Uni\u00e3o Leiria]] | caps2 = 89 | goals2 = 6\n| years3 = 2005 | clubs3 = [[Moreirense F.C.|Moreirense]] | caps3 = 10 | goals3 = 1 \n| years4 = 2006 | clubs4 = [[Al-Gharafa Sports Club|Al-Gharafa]] | caps4 = ? | goals4 = 4\n| years5 = 2006 | clubs5 = [[C.D. Aves|Aves]] | caps5 = 9 | goals5 = 0 \n| years6 = 2007 | clubs6 = [[Negeri Sembilan FA|Negeri Sembilan]] | caps6 = | goals6 =\n| years7 = 2007 | clubs7 = [[Doxa Katokopias FC|Doxa]] | caps7 = 7 | goals7 = 3\n| years8 = 2008 | clubs8 = [[Enosis Neon Paralimni FC|Enosis Neon]] | caps8 = 26 | goals8 = 13 \n| years9 = 2009\u20132011 | clubs9 = [[AEL Limassol]] | caps9 = 68 | goals9 = 24\n| years10 = 2011\u20132013 | clubs10 = [[AC Omonia|Omonia]] | caps10 = 53 | goals10 = 23\n| years11 = 2013 | clubs11 = [[C.D. Primeiro de Agosto|1\u00ba Agosto]] | caps11 = | goals11 =\n| years12 = 2014 | clubs12 = [[C.R. Ca\u00e1la|Ca\u00e1la]] | caps12 = 6 | goals12 = 1\n| totalcaps = 347 | totalgoals = 96\n| nationalyears1 = 2004\u20132005 | nationalteam1 = [[Angola national football team|Angola]] | nationalcaps1 = 11 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| club-update =\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n\n'''Frederico Castro Roque dos Santos''' (born 14 August 1979), known as '''Freddy''', is an [[Angola]]n retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\nHe spent most of his professional career in Portugal and [[Cyprus]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Malanje]], Freddy spent nine seasons at [[G.D. Estoril Praia]] \u2013 youth years comprised \u2013 playing two seasons in the [[Portuguese Second Division|Portuguese third division]] and one in [[Segunda Liga|the second]] as a senior. In [[2001\u201302 Primeira Liga|2001\u201302]] he made his [[Primeira Liga]] debut, being coached by a young [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]] and playing 22 matches (17 as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]]) as the team [[2002 UEFA Intertoto Cup|qualified]] to the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]; during four years, he only started in 16 of the league appearances he made.\n\nFreddy started 2005\u201306 with [[Moreirense F.C.]] in the second level, but transferred to [[Al-Gharafa Sports Club]] from [[Qatar]] in the next [[transfer window]]. He would also split the following campaign, between [[C.D. Aves]] (Portuguese top flight) and [[Malaysia]]'s [[Negeri Sembilan FA]], appearing in six [[AFC Cup]] games during his short spell with the latter and scoring three goals.<ref>[http://www.the-afc.com/en/afc-cup-2007/afc-cup-2007-schedule-results AFC Cup 2007 schedule and results]</ref>\n\nIn summer 2007, Freddy moved countries again, signing with [[Doxa Katokopias FC]] in Cyprus. In January of the following year, he stayed in the country and joined [[Enosis Neon Paralimni FC]].\n\nStill in Cyprus, in January 2009 Freddy signed for [[AEL Limassol]], scoring a combined 20 [[Cypriot First Division]] goals in his first two full seasons but seeing his team come out empty in silverware.\n\n==International career==\nFreddy appeared for [[Angola national football team|Angola]] during the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualification campaign]], scoring his only international goal in a 1\u20130 home win against [[Rwanda national football team|Rwanda]], on 5 September 2004.<ref>{{FIFA player|214349}}</ref> The ''Palancas Negras'' eventually qualified for the final stages in Germany \u2013 a first-ever \u2013 but he was overlooked for the final squad of 23.\n\n==Honours==\n'''Omonia'''\n*[[Cypriot Cup]]: [[2011\u201312 Cypriot Cup|2011\u201312]]\n*[[Cypriot Super Cup]]: 2012\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{NFT player|192}}\n*{{Soccerway|frederico-de-castro-roque-dos-santos/61449}}\n\n{{Cypriot First Division top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freddy}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Malanje Province]]\n[[Category:Portuguese people of Angolan descent]]\n[[Category:Angolan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Second Division players]]\n[[Category:G.D. Estoril Praia players]]\n[[Category:U.D. Leiria players]]\n[[Category:Moreirense F.C. players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Aves players]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League players]]\n[[Category:Al-Gharafa SC players]]\n[[Category:Malaysia Super League players]]\n[[Category:Negeri Sembilan FA players]]\n[[Category:Cypriot First Division players]]\n[[Category:Doxa Katokopias FC players]]\n[[Category:Enosis Neon Paralimni FC players]]\n[[Category:AEL Limassol players]]\n[[Category:AC Omonia players]]\n[[Category:Girabola players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Primeiro de Agosto players]]\n[[Category:C.R. Ca\u00e1la players]]\n[[Category:Angola international footballers]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate sportspeople in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Angolan expatriate sportspeople in Cyprus]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Angolan footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Angolan footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freddy_(Angolan_footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Operation Emery", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox nuclear weapons test\n|name                = Operation Emery\n|picture             = Operation_Emery_-_Baneberry.jpg\n|picture_description = Unexpected venting from the ''Baneberry'' nuclear test\n|country             = United States\n|test_site           = {{plainlist|\n*NTS Area 12, Rainier Mesa\n*NTS, Areas 1-4, 6-10, Yucca Flat}}\n|period              = 1970-1971\n|number_of_tests     = 16\n|test_type           = underground shaft, tunnel\n|max_yield           = {{convert|220|ktTNT|lk=in}}\n|previous_series     = [[Operation Mandrel]]\n|next_series         = [[Operation Grommet]]\n}}\n{{GeoGroup|article=Operation Emery}}\n\nThe '''United States's Emery nuclear test series'''<ref name=LT_1/> was a group of 16 [[nuclear weapons test]]s conducted in 1970-1971. These tests <ref group=note>A bomb test may be a salvo test, defined as two or more explosions \"where a period of time between successive individual explosions does not exceed 5 seconds and where the burial points of all explosive devices can be connected by segments of straight lines, each of them connecting two burial points and does not exceed 40 kilometers in length\". {{cite journal|first=V. N., Editor in Chief|last=Mikhailov|title=Catalog of World Wide Nuclear Testing|publisher=Begell-Atom, LLC|url=http://www.iss-atom.ru/ksenia/catal_nt/1.htm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426102201/http://www.iss-atom.ru/ksenia/catal_nt/1.htm|archivedate=April 26, 2014}}</ref> followed the ''[[Operation Mandrel]]'' series and preceded the ''[[Operation Grommet]]'' series.\n\nThe underground Baneberry test vented into the atmosphere. For descriptions, see [[Yucca Flat#Baneberry]] and [[List of military nuclear accidents#1970s]]\n\n{{See also|List of nuclear weapons tests of the United States}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ United States' Emery series tests and detonations\n|-\n!style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | Name <ref group=note>The US, France and Great Britain have code-named their test events, while the USSR and China did not, and therefore have only test numbers (with some exceptions &ndash; Soviet peaceful explosions were named). Word translations into English in parentheses unless the name is a proper noun. A dash followed by a number indicates a member of a salvo event. The US also sometimes named the individual explosions in such a salvo test, which results in \"name1 &ndash; 1(with name2)\". If test is canceled or aborted, then the row data like date and location discloses the intended plans, where known.</ref>\n!style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Date time ([[Universal Time|UT]])\n!style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | Local [[Time Zone|time zone]] <ref group=note>To convert the UT time into standard local, add the number of hours in parentheses to the UT time; for local daylight saving time, add one additional hour. If the result is earlier than 00:00, add 24 hours and subtract 1 from the day; if it is 24:00 or later, subtract 24 hours and add 1 to the day. Historical time zone data obtained from the [[tz database|IANA time zone database]].</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Time Zone Historical Database |publisher=iana.com |url=http://www.ietf.org/timezones/ |accessdate=March 8, 2014}}</ref>\n!style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[List of nuclear test sites|Location]] <ref group=note>Rough place name and a latitude/longitude reference; for rocket-carried tests, the launch location is specified before the detonation location, if known. Some locations are extremely accurate; others (like airdrops and space blasts) may be quite inaccurate. \"~\" indicates a likely pro-forma rough location, shared with other tests in that same area.</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | [[Elevation]] + height <ref group=note>Elevation is the ground level at the point directly below the explosion relative to sea level; height is the additional distance added or subtracted by tower, balloon, shaft, tunnel, air drop or other contrivance. For rocket bursts the ground level is \"N/A\". In some cases it is not clear if the height is absolute or relative to ground, for example, ''Plumbbob/John''. No number or units indicates the value is unknown, while \"0\" means zero. Sorting on this column is by elevation and height added together.</ref>\n!style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Delivery <ref group=note>Atmospheric, airdrop, balloon, gun, cruise missile, rocket, surface, tower, and barge are all disallowed by the [[Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty]]. Sealed shaft and tunnel are underground, and remained useful under the PTBT. Intentional cratering tests are borderline; they occurred under the treaty, were sometimes protested, and generally overlooked if the test was declared to be a peaceful use.</ref><br/>Purpose <ref group=note>Include weapons development, weapon effects, safety test, transport safety test, war, science, joint verification and industrial/peaceful, which may be further broken down.</ref>\n!style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[List of nuclear weapons|Device]] <ref group=note>Designations for test items where known, \"?\" indicates some uncertainty about the preceding value, nicknames for particular devices in quotes. This category of information is often not officially disclosed.</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | [[Nuclear weapon yield|Yield]] <ref group=note>Estimated energy yield in [[TNT equivalent|tons, kilotons, or megatons]]. A ton of TNT equivalent is defined as 4.184&nbsp;gigajoules (1&nbsp;gigacalorie).</ref>\n!style=\"background:#efefef;\" class=\"unsortable\" | [[Nuclear fallout|Fallout]] <ref group=note>Radioactive emission to the atmosphere aside from prompt neutrons, where known. The measured species is only iodine-131 if mentioned, otherwise it is all species. No entry means unknown, probably none if underground and \"all\" if not; otherwise notation for whether measured on the site only or off the site, where known, and the measured amount of radioactivity released.</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffdead;\" class=\"unsortable\" | References\n!style=\"background:#efefef;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! ''Scree-Acajou'' - 1{{anchor|Scree-Acajou}}\n| {{dts|1970|10|13}} 15:05:00.02\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | PST (-8&nbsp;hrs)<br/> || [[Nevada National Security Site|NTS]] Area U9itsx24 {{coord|37.1374|-116.03491|name=Scree-Acajou - 1|display=inline}}\n| {{sort|001019|}}{{convert|1269|m|abbr=on}} - {{convert|249.33|m|abbr=on}}\n| underground shaft,<br/>weapons development\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{sort|000010000|1&nbsp;kt}}\n| Venting detected on site, {{convert|11|Ci|GBq|abbr=on}}\n| <ref name=LT_1/><ref name=LT_150/><ref name=LT_48/><ref name=LT_44/><ref name=LT_34/><ref name=LT_6/>\n| Simultaneous, separate holes.\n|-\n! ''Scree-Alhambra'' - 2{{anchor|Scree-Alhambra}}\n| {{dts|1970|10|13}} 15:05:00.02\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | PST (-8&nbsp;hrs)<br/> || [[Nevada National Security Site|NTS]] Area U9itsz21 {{coord|37.13406|-116.0324|name=Scree-Alhambra - 2|display=inline}}\n| {{sort|001081|}}{{convert|1273|m|abbr=on}} - {{convert|192|m|abbr=on}}\n| underground shaft,<br/>weapons development\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{sort|000020000|2&nbsp;kt}}\n| Venting detected on site\n| <ref name=LT_1/><ref name=LT_150/><ref name=LT_48/><ref name=LT_34/><ref name=LT_6/><ref name=LT_57/>\n| Simultaneous, separate holes.\n|-\n! ''Scree-Chamois'' - 3{{anchor|Scree-Chamois}}\n| {{dts|1970|10|13}} 15:05:00.02\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | PST (-8&nbsp;hrs)<br/> || [[Nevada National Security Site|NTS]] Area U9itsz24 {{coord|37.13733|-116.03217|name=Scree-Chamois - 3|display=inline}}\n| {{sort|001275|}}{{convert|1275|m|abbr=on}} +\n| underground shaft,<br/>safety experiment\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{sort|000000000|less than 20&nbsp;kt}}\n| Venting detected on site\n| <ref name=LT_1/><ref name=LT_150/><ref name=LT_34/><ref name=LT_6/>\n| Simul