{"title_page": "1960 Washington Huskies football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| year              = 1960\n| team              = Washington Huskies\n| sport             = football\n|image = Washington Huskies logo.svg\n|image_size = 125\n| conference        = Athletic Association of Western Universities\n| division          = \n| short_conf        = AAWU\n| CoachRank         = 5\n| APRank            = 6\n| record            = 10\u20131\n| conf_record       = 4\u20130\n| head_coach        = [[Jim Owens]]\n| hc_year           = 4th\n| off_coach         = \n| def_coach         = Tom Tipps\n| asst_coach1       = [[Bert Clark]]  \n| captain           = Game captains\n| captain2          = \n| captain3          = \n| off_scheme        = \n| def_scheme        = \n| mvp               = \n| stadium           = [[Husky Stadium]]\n| champion          = Helms Poll national champion<br>Rose Bowl champion<br>AAWU champion\n| bowl              = [[1961 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]]\n| bowl_result       = W 17\u20137 vs. [[1960 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]]\n}}\n{{1960 AAWU football standings}}\nThe '''1960 Washington Huskies football team''' represented the [[University of Washington]] during the [[1960 NCAA University Division football season]].  Home games were played on campus in [[Seattle]] at [[Husky Stadium]].\n\nUnder fourth-year head coach [[Jim Owens]], Washington was 9\u20131 in the regular season and 4\u20130 in the [[Pac-12 Conference|Athletic Association of Western Universities]] (AAWU). Led on the field by senior quarterback [[Bob Schloredt]], an [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] the [[1959 College Football All-America Team|previous year]], the Huskies started the season ranked third. Schloredt broke his [[Clavicle|collarbone]] in the fifth game, against [[1960 UCLA Bruins football team|UCLA]],<ref name=ssbiuww>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PXApAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lecDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6906%2C553639 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington)|agency=Associated Press |title=Schloredt's shoulder broken in UW win |date=October 16, 1960 |page=}}</ref> and did not play again in the regular season.<ref name=sourbg>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EyRWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6858%2C3280481 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |title=Schloredt out until 'Rose Bowl game' |date=October 17, 1960 |page=3B}}</ref><ref name=slhtwin>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yzJWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wecDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6730%2C793393|newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington)|last=Missildine |first=Harry |title=Schloredt leads Huskies to win |date=January 3, 1961 |page=16}}</ref> Bob Hivner took over at quarterback and won the game plus the next five.\n\nA one-point loss on a last-minute field goal by [[1961 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]-bound [[1960 Navy Midshipmen football team|Navy]] two weeks earlier in Seattle was the season's only {{nowrap|blemish.<ref name=srnnh>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jKpWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=I-gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6705%2C780213|newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington)|agency=Associated Press |title=Mather punches field goal as Navy nips Huskies, 15-14 |date=October 2, 1960 |page=2, sports}}</ref><ref name=fgtrips>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CiRWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5846%2C52642|newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon)|agency=Associated Press |title=Field goal trips UW by 15-14 |date=October 2, 1960 |page=1B}}</ref>}} The Huskies returned to the [[1961 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] to meet the top-ranked [[1960 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota Golden Gophers]] of the [[Big Ten Conference]] on January 2. A {{nowrap|seven-point}} underdog,<ref name=ggtdedge>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yjJWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wecDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6846%2C535416 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington)|last=Missildine |first=Harry |title=Gophers given TD edge over Huskies |date=January 2, 1961 |page=14 }}</ref> {{nowrap|sixth-ranked}} Washington upset Minnesota {{nowrap|17\u20137}} for consecutive Rose Bowl {{nowrap|wins.<ref name=slhtwin/><ref name=chtribrb>{{cite news |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1961/01/03/page/47/article/gophers-beaten-in-rose-bowl-17-7 |newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune |last=Barry |first=Howard |title=Gophers beaten in Rose Bowl, 17-7 |date=January 3, 1961 |page=1, sec. 4}}</ref><ref name=erghwgop>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0f9VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6835%2C375135 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |last=Harvey |first=Paul, III |title=Huskies whip Gophers, 17\u20137 |date=January 3, 1961 |page=2B}}</ref>}} Schloredt returned at quarterback and was the player of the game for a second straight {{nowrap|year.<ref name=slhtwin/>}}\n\nThe [[1960 NCAA University Division football rankings|final rankings]] in this era were released at the end of the regular season, prior to the bowl {{nowrap|games.<ref name=minnessr>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zalWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4ecDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6695%2C4727363 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington)|agency=Associated Press |title=Gophers win title |date=November 30, 1960 |page=13}}</ref><ref name=gtfpol>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jFFYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cfcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2726%2C2802432 |newspaper=Bend Bulletin |location=(Oregon)|agency=UPI |title=Gophers top final poll |date=November 29, 1960 |page=3}}</ref>}} Washington outscored its  opponents <!--by a combined total of-->272&nbsp;to&nbsp;107.<ref>{{cite web|title=Washington Yearly Results (1960-1964)|publisher=David DeLassus|work=College Football Data Warehouse|accessdate=December 14, 2015|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/active/w/washington/1960-1964_yearly_results.php}}</ref>\nWashington finished the season ranked fifth and sixth in their respective polls.\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1960\n| poll = AP\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 17\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 3\n| opponent = [[1960 Pacific Tigers football team|Pacific (CA)]]\n| site_stadium = [[Husky Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Seattle|Seattle, WA]] <ref name=hsovst>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jjVWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GugDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6650%2C1108677\n|newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington)|agency=Associated Press |last=Hewins |first=Jack |title=Huskies overwhelm COP's Tigers, 55-6 |date=September 18, 1960 |page=2, sports}}</ref>\n| score = 55\u20136\n| attend = 39,047\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 24\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 3\n| opponent = [[1960 Idaho Vandals football team|Idaho]]\n| site_stadium = Husky Stadium\n| site_cityst = Seattle, WA <ref name=wwvnd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lTVWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GugDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6932%2C3439336 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington)|title=Foregone conclusion true -- Washington waxes Vandals |date=September 25, 1960 |page=2, sports}}</ref>\n| score = 41\u201312\n| attend = 35,996\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 1\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 3\n| opponent = [[1960 Navy Midshipmen football team|Navy]]\n| opprank = 17\n| site_stadium = Husky Stadium\n| site_cityst = Seattle, WA <ref name=srnnh/><ref name=fgtrips/>\n| score = 14\u201315\n| attend = 57,379\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 8\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 12\n| opponent = [[1960 Stanford Indians football team|Stanford]]\n| site_stadium = [[Stanford Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Stanford, California|Stanford,&nbsp;CA]]\n| score = 29\u201310\n| attend = 24,032\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 15\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 13\n| opponent = [[1960 UCLA Bruins football team|UCLA]]\n| opprank = 15\n| site_stadium = Husky Stadium\n| site_cityst = Seattle, WA <ref name=ssbiuww/>\n| score = 10\u20138\n| attend = 54,152\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 22\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| rank = 8\n| opponent = [[1960 Oregon State Beavers football team|Oregon State]]\n| opprank = 18\n| site_stadium = [[Multnomah Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland,&nbsp;OR]] <ref name=nposttrs>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FyRWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4195%2C4159903 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |last=Harvey |first=Paul, III |title=Huskies rally to nip Oregon Staters, 30-29 |date=October 23, 1960 |page=1B}}</ref>\n| score = 30\u201329\n| attend = 36,833\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 29\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 9\n| opponent = [[1960 Oregon Webfoots football team|Oregon]]\n| gamename = [[Oregon\u2013Washington football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = Husky Stadium\n| site_cityst = Seattle, WA <ref name=wnwfts>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=THApAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lecDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6667%2C5462092 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington)|agency=Associated Press |title=Washington nips Webfoots, 7-6, on Hivner-McKeta pass |date=October 30, 1960 |page=2, sports}}</ref>\n| score = 7\u20136\n| attend = 55,235\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 5\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 7\n| opponent = [[1960 USC Trojans football team|USC]]\n| site_stadium = [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum|Memorial Coliseum]]\n| site_cityst = [[Los Angeles|Los&nbsp;Angeles,&nbsp;CA]] <ref name=hsegrab>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=r3QRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7eIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3823%2C720272 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon)|agency=Associated Press |title=Huskies strike early, grab 34-0 shutout win over USC |date=November 6, 1960 |page=1B }}</ref>\n| score = 34\u20130\n| attend = 